div.p:
VAticinant. The soul is said to be in a vaticinant or parturient condition, when she hath some kind of sense and hovering knowledge of a thing, but yet cannot distinctly and fully, and commandingly represent it to her self, cannot plainly apprehend, much lesse comprehend the matter. The phrase is borrowed of Proclus, who describing the incomprehensiblenesse of God, and the desire of all things towards him, speaks thus; 
   〈 in non-Latin alphabet 〉
. Theolog Platon lib. 1. cap. 21. See Psychathan. lib. 3. cant. 3. stanz. 12. & 14.
